Files:
- e2e/security.e2e.ts (new file)

Context:
http-routes.ts lines 536-543 validates the Host header:
```typescript
if (!hostHeader || !isLocalhostHost(hostHeader)) {
  return new Response('Forbidden: invalid Host header', { status: 403 });
}
```

`isLocalhostHost` (line 121) checks against LOCALHOST_HOSTS set: `localhost`, `127.0.0.1`, `[::1]`, `[::ffff:127.0.0.1]` — with or without port suffix.

Unit tests exist at http-routes.test.ts line 834 but use mocked requests. This E2E test sends real HTTP requests.

Test approach — use `fetch` with custom Host header:
```typescript
// 403 for evil host
const res1 = await fetch(`http://127.0.0.1:${server.port}/health`, {
  headers: { Host: 'evil.com' },
});
expect(res1.status).toBe(403);
expect(await res1.text()).toContain('invalid Host header');

// 200/401 for localhost
const res2 = await fetch(`http://127.0.0.1:${server.port}/health`, {
  headers: { Host: `localhost:${server.port}` },
});
expect([200, 401]).toContain(res2.status); // depends on auth
```

Note: Node.js `fetch` allows overriding the Host header. Some HTTP clients strip it — verify that the test framework supports this.

Constraints:
- Use the standard mcpServer fixture.
- Test at least 3 evil hosts and 3 valid localhost hosts.
- The /health endpoint without auth returns 200 with minimal response — use it for the valid host tests.

Files:
- e2e/security.e2e.ts (same file as US-001)

Context:
http-routes.ts lines 546-562:
```typescript
// --- CORS protection ---
const origin = req.headers.get('Origin');
if (origin) {
  // Chrome extension requests carry an Origin of `chrome-extension://...`
  if (!origin.startsWith('chrome-extension://')) {
    return new Response('Forbidden: browser cross-origin request', { status: 403 });
  }
  // Set CORS headers for valid extension requests
  headers['Access-Control-Allow-Origin'] = origin;
  headers['Access-Control-Allow-Methods'] = 'GET, POST, DELETE, OPTIONS';
  headers['Access-Control-Allow-Headers'] = 'Content-Type, Authorization';
}
```

Test approach:
```typescript
// 403 for browser origin
const res1 = await fetch(`http://localhost:${server.port}/health`, {
  headers: { Origin: 'https://evil.com' },
});
expect(res1.status).toBe(403);
expect(await res1.text()).toContain('cross-origin');

// OK for chrome-extension origin
const res2 = await fetch(`http://localhost:${server.port}/health`, {
  headers: { Origin: 'chrome-extension://abcdefghijk' },
});
expect(res2.status).toBe(200);

// OK for no origin (MCP client)
const res3 = await fetch(`http://localhost:${server.port}/health`);
expect(res3.status).toBe(200);
```

Files:
- e2e/security.e2e.ts (same file)

Context:
mcp-tool-dispatch.ts line 34: `const MAX_CONCURRENT_DISPATCHES_PER_PLUGIN = 5;`
Line 363-368:
```typescript
if (currentDispatches >= MAX_CONCURRENT_DISPATCHES_PER_PLUGIN) {
  return { content: [{ type: 'text', text: `Too many concurrent dispatches for plugin "${pluginName}" (limit: ${MAX_CONCURRENT_DISPATCHES_PER_PLUGIN}). Wait for in-flight requests to complete.` }], isError: true };
}
```

The concurrency is per-plugin, tracked in `state.pluginDispatchCounts`.

Test approach: Use the e2e-test plugin's `slow_with_progress` tool which takes time to complete. Fire 6 concurrent calls:
```typescript
const calls = Array.from({ length: 6 }, () =>
  mcpClient.callTool('e2e_test_slow_with_progress', { durationMs: 5000 }, { timeout: 30_000 })
);
const results = await Promise.all(calls);

// 5 should succeed, 1 should fail with concurrency error
const successes = results.filter(r => !r.isError);
const failures = results.filter(r => r.isError);
expect(successes.length).toBe(5);
expect(failures.length).toBe(1);
expect(failures[0].content).toContain('Too many concurrent dispatches');
```

Note: The e2e-test plugin needs a matching tab that is ready (adapter injected). Use the standard test server setup.

Alternatively, use browser tools with 'auto' permission — `browser_list_tabs` is fast so 5 might complete before the 6th arrives. Use a slow browser tool or add a brief delay. Actually, the race is tricky. A more reliable approach: use `browser_execute_script` with a script that sleeps, keeping all 5 dispatches alive while sending the 6th.

Or simpler: use the e2e-test plugin's `slow_with_progress` tool with `{ durationMs: 10000 }` — each call holds a dispatch slot for 10 seconds, plenty of time to fire the 6th.

Constraints:
- This test needs the e2e-test plugin with a ready tab.
- Use test.slow() since multiple concurrent long-running dispatches are involved.
- The `slow_with_progress` tool needs the e2e-test adapter injected into a matching tab.

Files:
- e2e/security.e2e.ts (same file)

Context:
extension-handlers.ts `rejectAllPendingConfirmations` (line ~339 per unit test reference) is called when the extension WebSocket disconnects. It rejects all pending confirmation promises, which causes the MCP tool call to return an error.

http-routes.ts line 636-638 (approximate — on extension disconnect, calls `rejectAllPendingConfirmations`).

Test approach:
1. Set browser permission to 'ask'
2. Open side panel, wait for connected
3. Call `browser_list_tabs` — confirmation dialog appears
4. Instead of clicking Allow/Deny, close the extension context (or navigate away from the extension page)
5. Verify the MCP client receives an error quickly

Closing the extension context should disconnect the WebSocket. Use:
```typescript
const [result] = await Promise.all([
  mcpClient.callTool('browser_list_tabs', {}, { timeout: 35_000 }),
  (async () => {
    // Wait for confirmation to arrive (badge shows '1')
    const sw = await getBackgroundWorker(extensionContext);
    await waitFor(async () => (await getBadgeText(sw)) === '1', 15_000, 200, 'badge === 1');

    // Disconnect the extension by closing the context
    await extensionContext.close();
  })(),
]);

expect(result.isError).toBe(true);
// Error should mention extension disconnect, not timeout
```

Note: After closing the context, the server should detect the WebSocket close and reject pending confirmations. The MCP client should get the error much faster than the 30s dispatch timeout.

Constraints:
- This test destroys the extension context, so it should be the last test or use its own isolated setup.
- Cannot verify recovery in the same test since the context is gone — that can be a separate test.

